  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1718539873" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1718539873" />
    <a title="Brian " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30718608-brian"><img alt="Brian " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1567218975p2/30718608.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1718539873?book_show_action=true">Aug 04, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brian " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brian " href="/user/show/30718608-brian">Brian </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/315939.Ubik">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/30718608-brian?shelf=sci-fi">sci-fi</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/30718608-brian?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/30718608-brian?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1718539873" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1807075133027265450"> I have one all-time favorite movie (aside from adaptions of Hamlet): The Matrix. I novelized this movie before writing my own novel (and am still processing). I asked Goodreads if they knew of any books like this movie, and I received two suggestions by P.K. Dick, “Ubik,” and “Do Androids Dream of Electric Sheep?” <br/><br/> For some time this year I left the “pleasures” of reading to pursue my dreams of writing. I set out a plan: read literary magazines and short stories, write literary stories and get </span>
  <span id="freeText1807075133027265450" style="display:none"> I have one all-time favorite movie (aside from adaptions of Hamlet): The Matrix. I novelized this movie before writing my own novel (and am still processing). I asked Goodreads if they knew of any books like this movie, and I received two suggestions by P.K. Dick, “Ubik,” and “Do Androids Dream of Electric Sheep?” <br /><br /> For some time this year I left the “pleasures” of reading to pursue my dreams of writing. I set out a plan: read literary magazines and short stories, write literary stories and get published, publish a bunch and get rapport, writes a novel and publish the novel with that rapport. So, that took my fire away. I turned my whole purpose of reading into a goal tainted by selfish ambition. I started to lose my fire to write fiction, even considered quitting altogether.<br /> <br /> And now I’ve read “Ubik,” by P.K. Dick.<br /><br /> I have a new rule now, just for me: Read the books that make you want to keep reading more books. I want to write for pleasure now, not to achieve some pompous goal to prove something to myself only to cry I have no more worlds to conquer like Alexander the Great. The joy and pleasure of the story fills that desire, that void. I do this when I sing too. When I sing and play guitar to impress others, I fail to perform well. When I do it to bring myself into that sanctuary of peace and pleasure, and emotional drifting, I sound good, and others feel the pleasure I try to bring to myself.<br /><br /> Sorry about all the autobiographical stuff here.<br /><br /> I’m happy and excited. I feel like a kid who opened a Christmas present, and the thing he finds came from something he made up in his dreams. I’ve been searching for this. It’s all I’ve wanted. P.K. Dick has strong storytelling capabilities. He takes you on a path with a multitude of turns. You think you know how this will play out, and then you don’t and you do again, and then you give up and feel suspense because “what’s going on?!” <br /><br /> This story sets complicated futuristic ideas and weaves a complex plot around those ideas. A war wages between psychics digging in minds for info. Anti-psychics have the power to block them. The two businesses war against each other like mob bosses. The good guy gets set up and trapped in a room with the world’s top quality talents, and a bomb explodes. Let the games begin! The world starts to regress. A dead man sends messages that the reader has died but the messenger still lives. People start decaying rapidly and shrink into tiny skulls and layers of flesh. <br /><br /> You have to read this one if you like Sci-Fi, especially if you liked the Matrix. I see how this may have strongly influenced the Wachowski’s. I also see how Dick may have influenced King in his DT Series.<br /><br /> I can’t wait to read more of his stuff! He keeps me wanting to read, and reminds me of my best reason to write fiction.<br /><br /> For a thorough and concise overview of the complexities of the story, I recommend our friend Cecily's review: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/580647608?book_show_action=false&amp;from_review_page=1">https://www.goodreads.com/review/show...</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="1807075133027265450" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


